<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 93 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: Agreement desirable
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
I EARN an income of Pounds 10,000 and have unearned income of Pounds 40,000.
I have assets as a result of an inheritance of Pounds 500,000 including our
house which is worth about Pounds 100,000. My husband to be has no assets
and earns about Pounds 25,000.
Much as I love him, our relationship has been volatile to date. If we marry
and divorce in five years with no children and no changes in our financial
positions, is there any risk the Courts could award him any of my capital?
There must always be some risk of the kind which you envisage on divorce,
since the Court has power to direct whatever financial settlement it deems
just in all the circumstances. Hence a contractual agreement settling the
parties rights (in the absence of children) is desirable.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
