<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Middle East and jobs news
weaken Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
DISQUIETING news about employment and continuing unease about developments
in the Middle East drove US share prices sharply lower for the second
consecutive day, writes Karen Zagor in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed off 17.29 at 3,251.67 after dropping
more than 36 points at mid-day. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500
ended 1.66 lower at 429.07, while the Amex composite finished down 1.28 at
395.84, and the Nasdaq composite down 1.00 at 677.21. Volume on the NYSE was
265m shares, and declines outnumbered rises by 1,175 to 677.
Profit-taking was a factor in the morning decline, but there was no comfort
to be found in the unexpectedly weak employment figures for December.
The market had expected non-farm payrolls to rise by about 83,000, but the
increase was a more modest 64,000, with the rate of civilian unemployment
unchanged at 7.3 per cent.
In addition, investors remain concerned about the prospects of renewed
hostilities in the Middle East which could hurt US consumer confidence and
interfere with economic recovery.
In the retail sector, Woolworth fell Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 28 7/8 after
the company had revealed a disappointing 1 per cent improvement in domestic
same-store sales for the Christmas period. An analyst at Dean Witter
downgraded his investment rating on the stock and reduced fourth quarter
earnings estimates.
Trading was also heavy in Wal-Mart, the biggest US retailer in terms of
sales, which fell Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 59 3/4 in spite of a 10 per cent
advance in same-store sales.
A number of drug company stocks were actively traded including Merck, up
Dollars 1 at Dollars 42 1/2 and Bristol-Myers Squibb, down Dollars 1/4 at
Dollars 62 5/8 . Johnson &amp; Johnson added Dollars 1 to Dollars 46 5/8 .
IBM lost Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 46 1/2 , a new 52-week low.
On the Nasdaq market Intel slipped Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 98 3/4 ,
Microsoft eased Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 87 1/8 and Novell fell Dollars 1/8
to Dollars 30 1/4 . The Federal Trade Commission plans to meet in early
February to decide whether it will take anti-trust action against Microsoft,
the world's biggest supplier of computer software, which has been expanding
into a number of market segments.
Biogen soared Dollars 4 to Dollars 43 1/4 following a strong endorsement by
Bear Stearns, which rated the stock a top biotechnology issue.
Canada
TORONTO stocks ended a week of heavy trading on a losing note, as did most
important world markets.
The composite index fell 7.10 points, or 0.21%, to 3311.77, for a loss on
the week of about 38 points.
Declining issues were ahead of advances by 318 to 294. Volume fell to
50,887,000 shares from 58,131,000 shares yesterday, and trading value was
CDollars 385.7m as compared with CDollars 457.6m on Thursday.
Among the sub-indices, nine of the 14 were lower and one was unchanged.
Industrial products were off 0.97% on index, while golds and energy fell
moderately.
