<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 93 / TGWU gives backing to electoral reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE prospect of Labour endorsing some version of proportional representation
came closer yesterday when the biggest union affiliated to the party gave
strong backing to electoral reform.
Mr Bill Morris, general secretary of the TGWU general union, said the party
could no longer support a status quo which continued to return governments
backed by only a minority of the popular vote.
'The electoral options should be actively examined,' he said. 'I would not
be averse to seeing some sort of new arrangement, but exactly which system I
do not know.' Mr Morris stressed that this was the consensus of an internal
union debate on the subject.
'The great weight of opinion has shifted in favour of some sort of change',
he said. The union's change of position may have a significant influence on
the final outcome of Labour's commission on electoral reform under Lord
Plant.
A two-day meeting to discuss systems for the Commons ended inconclusively
yesterday with the committee reporting that it was examining three systems.
One is the existing first-past-the-post system; a second is the alternative
vote system in which voters number candidates in order of preference, and if
no candidate wins more than 50 per cent of the votes then the votes for the
candidate at the bottom of the poll are reallocated among all the other
candidates until somebody acquires more than 50 per cent.
But the system thought most likely to be adopted if first-past-the-post is
rejected is a version of the alternative member system in which 150 Commons
seats would be reserved for 'best losers' and allocated by means of an
equation intended to reflect the performance of parties on a proportional
basis. A final report to the national executive committee is due to be
submitted in April.
Support for proportional representation from the left-of-centre TGWU has
taken some observers by surprise as the union continues to be associated
with conservative positions on many other issues, such as links with the
unions.
The union seems more disillusioned than many others with the Labour party.
It is to scale down its affiliation with the party, reflecting both its
falling membership and a change in its political priorities, although it
will still wield 10 per cent of the vote at this year's party conference.
Of the other large unions the GMB general union continues to support a
first-past-the-post system while the AEEU engineering and electricians'
union has long been a supporter of electoral reform.
</TEXT>
