<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 93 / Unions may lose more members
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIONS are likely to lose a further 8 per cent of their members this year,
Mr Bill Morris, general secretary of the TGWU general union, said yesterday.
In 1991 unions affiliated to the Trades Union Congress lost only about 5 per
cent of their members and last year's figure is expected to be only slightly
higher.
However, a disproportionate number of the big job losses announced over the
past few weeks have come from large unionised companies. There will also be
greater pressure on jobs in the public sector with this year expected to be
the toughest for them since the recession began. The membership of TUC
unions will probably fall below 7m.
The TGWU expects to lose about 8 per cent of its members - a slightly better
record than in the past two years - and total membership will probably fall
to just under 1m. The union has been hit by some examples of derecognition
in the past year, but most of the membership loss has come through
redundancies.
Mr Morris said the financial and organisational state of the union had
improved substantially since he took office nine months ago and would
continue to do so this year.
For the past year the TGWU is expected to report a surplus of nearly Pounds
5m compared with a deficit of Pounds 12m in 1991. That was achieved through
cost-cutting and increasing subscriptions. Mr Morris stressed that internal
reorganisation would continue this year.
He said that the union had 'moved beyond factionalism and is now driven by a
unity of purpose that has not been seen for a very long time'. He even
predicted some areas of membership growth this year, particularly in civil
air transport and among women.
Union mergers could also boost the union and yesterday Mr Morris met leaders
of FTAT, the 34,000-strong furniture union, to discuss possible terms for a
merger.
He called the planned change to the law which would require more regular
approval of the automatic check-off of union subscriptions by employers 'a
vindictive act by small-minded people'. But he added that it could have the
benefit of forcing activists to collect union dues personally thus helping
to put them back in touch with the members.
</TEXT>
