<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / International Company News: Ahold reports turnover in US up
12.9% to Dollars 6.3bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AHOLD, the Dutch-based supermarket group which owns four big US grocery
store chains, said 1992 turnover rose by 7.3 per cent to Fl 22.3bn (Dollars
12.3bn), with US turnover growth outstripping the gain posted in the
Netherlands.
The US, which generally accounts for roughly half of group sales, saw a 12.9
per cent turnover rise to Dollars 6.3bn. Of this increase, 7.2 per cent was
due to the fact that New York-based Tops Markets had been consolidated for
only 39 weeks in 1991 compared with a full 53 weeks in 1992.
Dutch turnover was up 9.1 per cent at Fl 11.2bn.
Ahold, which is due to publish 1992 profits on March 18, said overall
turnover would have been 3.7 percentage points higher if it had not been for
the dollar's decline. Partly compensating for this was the 53-week financial
year, which flattered sales figures by around 2 percentage points.
</TEXT>
