<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This week's slide in ALUMINIUM prices on the London Metal Exchange continued
yesterday, with the three months delivery contract falling another Dollars
14.50 to Dollars 1,217.50 a tonne. Dealers said US selling had prompted a
renewed test of support at Dollars 1,215 a tonne. NICKEL prices also added
to Wednesday's decline as profit-taking following recent strength continued
to undermine the market. The three months price closed at Dollars 6,247.50 a
tonne, down Dollars 50 on the day, but steadied a little in after hours
trading. COPPER prices reached three-month dollar highs early in the day but
ended only marginally higher following hedge selling and profit-taking in
the afternoon. The three months price reached Dollars 2,392 a tonne before
ending at Dollars 2,355 a tonne, up Dollars 5. Dealers said expectations of
further declines in LME warehouse stocks and continued Chinese buying helped
to hold the market above Dollars 2,500. COFFEE prices rallied following
their recent slump, aided by profit-taking on short positions. The London
robusta March futures prices closed Dollars 14 higher at Dollars 945 a
tonne.
Compiled from Reuters
