<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / International Company News: Zuckerman seals NY Daily News
takeover
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Mortimer Zuckerman, the real estate investor and magazine publisher,
yesterday completed his acquisition of The Daily News, the New York tabloid
newspaper once owned by the late Mr Robert Maxwell.
The Canadian-born Mr Zuckerman, who already owns the weekly US News &amp; World
Report and The Atlantic, an upmarket monthly literary and political
magazine, is expected to assume ownership of the newspaper today. . become
chairman and co-publisher of The Daily News, while Mr Fred Drasner, a close
associate, will be chief executive and co-publisher.
Mr Drasner, who shares management responsibility with Mr Zuckerman at US
News &amp; World Report, has played a leading role in reaching agreements with
nine of the 10 trade unions at The Daily News, which has a daily circulation
of nearly 800,000.
Although the actual purchase price has not been disclosed, it is believed to
be in the region of Dollars 36m. Mr Zuckerman, who is also editor-in-chief
of US News &amp; World Report, has overcome financial, trade union and legal
obstacles in his quest for the New York paper in recent months.
While The Daily News has been making losses, Mr Zuckerman has said he is
confident he will return the paper to the black, in part by luring back lost
advertising with improved political, business and investigative coverage.
Last autumn, Mr Zuckerman succeeded in striking accords with union
representatives who preferred his offer to that of Mr Conrad Black, the
Canadian who owns The Daily Telegraph in London. More recently, he has won a
court battle with the typographers' union, which previously held life-time
employment contracts.
The one union that has been least willing to yield to Mr Zuckerman's request
for freedom to hire and fire editorial staff has been the Newspaper Guild.
</TEXT>
