FT  08 JAN 93 / UK Company News: Druck declines 27% but orders increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Druck Holdings, the Leicester-based manufacturer of electronic pressure
measuring devices, yesterday reported lower first-half sales and profits but
said orders were up, writes Paul Taylor.
Pre-tax profits in the six months to September 30 fell by 27 per cent from
Pounds 2.41m to Pounds 1.75m on turnover which slipped by 6 per cent to
Pounds 12.7m (Pounds 13.5m). Earnings per share fell to 18p (23.3p), however
the interim dividend is being maintained at 3.4p.
Mr John Salmon, chairman, said: 'Due to a number of factors the first half
results are down on the same period last year, but I am confident that this
deficit will be partially, if not wholly, reversed by the end of the full
year.'
He said orders were 6 per cent ahead for the first six months and had moved
further ahead since September. Orders from Germany, which had lagged other
markets, had increased considerably, as had export orders.
