<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tonight, and for the next two nights, Arena's The Graham Greene Trilogy (BBC
2, 9.30) offers the unmissable opportunity to become immersed in the
conscience-ridden torments of Greene-land. Greene, who died in 1991, called
writing his disease. The first instalment narrates his career as far as
Mexico and The Power and the Glory.
I suspect that the main effect of 'how to' gardening programmes on TV is to
sow disillusionment. Novice gardeners wonder gloomily why the muddy,
bug-eaten reality never corresponds to what they saw being effortlessly
accomplished on the box. BBC 2's Front Gardens (8.30) invites garden
designers to transform tiny off-street patches according to their owners'
hearts' desires. On C4 at 9.00 there is the other kind of gardening
programme. In A Count of Flowers, ace garden-presenter Roy Lancaster begins
the first of a two-part exploration of the fabulously lovely gardens of La
Mortola in Italy. Joanna Kanska, so memorable as the Polish heroine of 'Very
Peculiar Practice', returns to the screen as a sexy Russian in Love Hurts
(BBC1, 9.30)
</TEXT>
