<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / Clarke seeks radical rejig of police control
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS FOR a radical reorganisation of the police, amounting to the virtual
nationalisation of police authorities in England and Wales, are to be
considered next week by a special cabinet committee chaired by Mr John
Major.
The proposals, produced by Mr Kenneth Clarke, home secretary, have aroused
strong dissent within the government and are vigorously opposed by local
authorities and most chief constables.
Mr Clarke's scheme would in effect abolish the current arrangements for
police management, which balance local and national control.
Government appointees and not local councillors would form the majority on
police committees. Funding would be transferred wholesale to Whitehall in
place of the current half-and-half arrangement.
The number of police authorities in England and Wales would be reduced from
the current 43, possibly to as few as 25.
The Association of Chief Police Offices will this weekend hold an emergency
conference to consider the proposals. It is almost certain to express
reservations to the Home Office, with some members concerned at the
constitutional implications of increasing the home secretary's powers to
direct the police.
Mr Michael Howard, environment secretary, is believed to oppose the plans,
considering it undesirable to weaken local authorities further. A cabinet
committee could not agree on the issue before Christmas, necessitating the
prime minister's intervention.
The associations representing the local authorities affected, both Labour
and Tory-controlled, have written to the prime minister urging him to reject
the proposed changes.
Mr Jeremy Beecham, chairman of the Labour-dominated Association of
Metrpolitan Authorities, said: 'These proposals would virtually create a
nationalised police force, run by unelected and unaccountable placemen, with
budgets totally controlled by the government. This would be dreadful for the
policing of our communities and for our democracy.'
Under the existing so-called 'tripartite system', elected councillors fill
two thirds of the places on police authorities with the other third going to
magistrates. Of police funding, 51 per cent comes from central government
and 49 per cent from local government.
The government is calling on businesses to fund schemes aimed at cutting
crime. Business and industrial leaders will be recruited to a new National
Board for Crime Prevention, which will welcome ideas and funding from the
private sector in what is hoped will be a fresh approach to tackling urban
crime.
</TEXT>
