<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / Ofgas attacks British Gas on service charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH GAS became embroiled in another row with its regulator yesterday
when Sir James McKinnon, director-general of Ofgas, accused the company of
making big increases in service charges.
Sir James said British Gas was trying to claw back the profits it had lost
from reduced gas prices by raising service charges by more than the rate of
inflation. British Gas has been forced by the regulator to reduce domestic
gas prices through a tough new formula.
Sir James said: 'A lot of people are getting a Pounds 20 benefit from lower
gas prices, but those on British Gas's 3-star service are losing Pounds 10
of that from higher prices.'
Mr Simon Kirk, British Gas director of marketing, said there were some
'astonishing' allegations in Ofgas's announcement. He said in an interview
on BBC radio that Sir James's allegations were 'scurrilous and
irresponsible'.
But British Gas said average price rises for servicing across the country
had been 7.9 per cent in April last year and admitted that in some regions
prices had increased by as much as 11 per cent. 'We're adding value to those
service packages at a price we think customers can afford,' a company
official said. He added that British Gas's service business has been rising
by about 20 per cent a year for the past five years. At the same time,
British Gas has only about 25 per cent of that service market.
Mr Ian Powe, head of the Gas Consumers' Council, the body which represents
customers, said that 18 months ago competitors in the service market were
complaining that British Gas was undercutting their prices and that they
could not compete. 'Now it is a totally different scene, prices are up and
consumers are not doing too well,' he said.
Mr Powe said he was completing a review of service and installation charges
that will be ready by the end of January. But the Gas Consumers' Council and
Ofgas have no powers to act in the service market.
Large contracts for the supply of water, gas, electricity, transport and
telecommunications services to public networks will have to be advertised in
the EC Official Journal under new regulations which come into force on
January 13.
