<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / More BR sell-off details expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE DETAILS of the government's plans to privatise British Rail are
expected to emerge in the next few weeks. The aim is to restore the momentum
of moves towards sell-off, which critics have described as unworkable and
stalled.
The series of announcements planned includes publication of the rail bill on
January 20. Ministers will launch a publicity offensive to win support for
their privatisation plans, which have run into opposition from senior
Conservatives, as well as Labour and the rail lobby.
Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary, will soon name the new regulator
who is to oversee rail privatisa-tion.
Details of the rules for charging train operators for using the track are
also due to be published. The first half-dozen or so of the expected 30 to
40 passenger-service franchises will also be announced.
Mr MacGregor will use the Department of Transport's question slot in the
Commons on Monday to reply to his critics.
Later that day he will be appearing before the transport committee. Although
he is due to give evidence on the transport implications of the Autumn
Statement, he is likely to be questioned on the implications of BR's tighter
funding over the next three years on the privatisation plans.
He will also defend the government's plans in the Commons on Tuesday in a
debate on BR privatisation launched by Labour.
The first franchises will be based on five to eight new profit centres,
formed from BR's 19 existing operating divisions. These will operate as
'ghost' franchises under BR management until the first round of franchising
next year, offering the private sector an idea of what sort of business
opportunities are likely to be available.
Likely candidates include the London, Tilbury and Southend Line and Chiltern
Line services from London Marylebone.
