<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / Sellafield discharge figures revised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE public consultation period for British Nuclear Fuels' new Thorp plant at
Sellafield, Cumbria, due to end on Monday, was yesterday extended by two
weeks after BNF issued new figures showing that some past radioactive
discharges had been slightly higher than it had previously indicated.
BNF said in a letter to the pollution inspectorate that the 'minor errors'
were due to a change in sampling techniques and to confusion between
gigabecquerels (a billion units of radioactivity) and megabecquerels (a
million units).
Dr Patrick Green of Friends of the Earth, the pressure group which yesterday
published its own 160-page submission to the inspectorate, said: 'This
raises even more uncertainty about what has been put out in the past, so how
are we to be sure of what they are putting out in the future?'
The revised figures show that the average discharges to the air of alpha
radiation from the site's main stacks between 1988 and 1991 had been 0.9 GBq
instead of the previously reported 0.7 GBq. However average beta radiation
emitted had been 10 GBq instead of the previously reported 11 GBq.
BNF said: 'The overall impact of this re-estimation is so small that in
BNF's view the proposed discharge limits will not be affected.' The site
selected by UK Nirex for its proposed Pounds 2.5bn underground nuclear-waste
repository at Sellafield is a poor one, according to a report by
Environmental Resources, an independent consultancy.
The report is the latest and most critical in a series commissioned by
Cumbria County Council. It suggests that groundwater from the repository
could reach the surface in about 300 years.
</TEXT>
