<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / Architects' confidence 'lowest since early 1991'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ARCHITECTS ARE expecting a grim 1993 and confidence is at its lowest level
since the start of 1991, the Royal Institute of British Architects says in a
report published today.
Architects in every region expect a fall in workloads in the first half of
this year, with the gloomiest being those in Northern Ireland and south-east
England.
The figures coincide with a Gallup poll for Building magazine of 80 building
contractors, materials producers and consultancies which found that 53 per
cent believed the UK market would improve a little this year.
But building sector insolvencies are expected to continue at the same or a
higher rate by 89 per cent of those polled. More than half of the 33
housebuilders interviewed believe sales will be higher in the next three
months than in the previous quarter, and 55 per cent plan to build more
private-sector houses this year.
The institute says only 15 per cent of architects' firms expect any
improvement in workloads over the next six months while 47 per cent expect a
fall.
In the third quarter of last year a rise in public spending helped new
commissions to steady after marked falls in the first two quarters of the
year.
New commissions for housing and offices show marked declines in the quarter
although work on production drawings increased.
The institute sees this as the best sign in the figures because it may
signal that projects put on hold during the recession are gradually being
'unfrozen'.
Retail, leisure and industrial sectors all showed a decline in new
commissions.
RIBA Leads, Carmargue House, Wellington Road, Cheltenham, Gloucestershire
GL52 2AG. Pounds 125 a year; members Pounds 99.
