<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / AT&amp;T Istel to freeze pay and cut workforce
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SALARIES have been frozen for this year and some 375 jobs are likely to go
over the next six months at AT&amp;T Istel.
The company, a subsidiary of American Telephone and Telegraph of the US,
used to be the computing arm of British Leyland and is now one of the
largest UK-based computing services companies.
The measures indicate the impact of the recession on such companies, which
depend heavily on large-scale project work from big corporate clients.
Mr Peter Teague, the new chief executive of AT&amp;T Istel, said it was being
forced to rein back ambitious growth plans. 'We decided we had no
alternative but to take this painful action,' he said.
AT&amp;T Istel said the measures continued policies initiated by Mr Chris
Chiles, the previous chief executive.
The company, based in Redditch, Hereford and Worcester, employs 2,200 people
in the UK and a further 1,800 in continental Europe. It last made staff
redundant two years ago when 150 jobs were lost. A voluntary redundancy
scheme is now planned.
Last year Istel turned over Pounds 200m but is not thought to have made a
profit.
It specialises in systems integration and communication services including
electronic data interchange for a variety of industries including
manufacturing, finance and travel.
Computing services companies are a sensitive indicator of the health of
industry because new business initiatives have to be underpinned by computer
systems.
Dr Douglas Eyeions, director-general of the Computing Services Association,
a trade organisation, said there was little new work in the computer
industry.
Many were pinning their hopes on work from the health service and the
government's market-testing programme, which could result in some Pounds
750m of computing contracts being offered to the private sector over the
next few years.
AT&amp;T alliance, Page 15
