<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / Car industry is cautious over upturn: Sales for December 37
per cent higher; Ford loses lead to Rover for first time since 1984
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A 37 per cent rise in new car sales last month compared with December 1991
does not signal that the motor industry has begun a sharp move out of
recession, industry leaders warned last night.
A significant factor in December's sharp rise was unusually large sales by
some motor companies to their employees which had a disproportionate effect,
in percentage terms, on the second smallest sales month of the year.
The 79,903 cars registered in December brought the total for all of last
year to 1,593,601 - only 0.08 per cent above the depressed level of 1991,
according to Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders statistics issued
yesterday. In December 1991 only 58,274 cars were sold, amounting to just
3.6 per cent of the year's total market.
However, last month's figures meant that new car sales rose in each month of
the final quarter of last year, indicating that a modest, sustainable
recovery is under way after the market's earlier collapse from a record 2.3m
units in 1989. Last year's sales were down 21 per cent on the 2m achieved in
1990 and 31 per cent down on the 1989 record.
Reflecting the stance of most UK motor chiefs, Mr Ian Mc-Allister, chairman
of Ford of Britain, said last night that 'it would be unwise to read too
much into the dramatic rise in December sales, where special factors were
involved. Incoming orders suggest that the underlying trend is showing a 10
per cent improvement, which is good news in itself.' He spoke as Ford came
to terms with the fact that in December it lost the UK market leadership -
to Rover - for the first time since 1984.
Rover's December sales rose two thirds compared with last year to give it a
market share for the month of 25.48 per cent compared with 16.65 per cent
for Ford and 13.8 per cent for Vauxhall. Rover acknowledged that some 4,000
cars had been sold at discounts of up to 25 per cent to employees, and for
the year as a whole it trailed well behind Ford - still in first place with
22.17 per cent.
With the share of sales accounted for by imports also being reduced
slightly, Sir Hal Miller, the society's chief executive, said the industry
was 'delighted' with the figures.
Volkswagen is to raise prices on its cars and vans by about 4.9 per cent
from January 18. The average price of VW cars will have risen by about 8 per
cent in two months.
VAG (UK), the importer bought by VW from Lonrho on January 1, blamed the
devaluation of sterling for the new increase.
