<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / Further trials loom for Lamont: The difficulties the
chancellor faces in preparing the Budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE trials of Mr Norman Lamont show few signs of ending. Having survived the
trauma of sterling's devaluation last September, the chancellor faces a
difficult two months in which to fashion his Budget.
The main challenge for Mr Lamont and his Treasury advisers - who will
discuss the Budget today and tomorrow at his residence in Chevening, Kent -
will be how to tackle the mounting financial deficit without constraining
any fragile recovery.
One option for the chancellor is to announce in March a modest increase in
taxation of perhaps Pounds 4bn with the aim of reining back the mounting
public sector borrowing requirement.
As any tax rise is likely to be unpopular, he may also want to cut interest
rates, now at 7 per cent, and announce measures to help industry. He will
almost certainly take some action to reduce the rise in the deficit, which
according to the Treasury's published assumptions will reach Pounds 37bn
this financial year and about Pounds 44bn in 1993-94.
Mr Lamont could gain an extra Pounds 4bn or so in tax revenues in 1993-94
through measures such as extending value added tax to newspapers and heating
bills, imposing an environmentally helpful increase in petrol tax and
ordering non-indexation of some income-tax allowances.
Without such measures and using calculations based on a rule of thumb used
by the Treasury to link likely deficits will projected growth, the PSBR
could easily stay at Pounds 40bn to Pounds 50bn until at least 1995-96.
On the worst-case assumption that growth remains extremely weak over these
years, the deficit could climb by then to Pounds 75.8bn or 11.2 per cent of
gross domestic product.
This would be a far cry from the position in the late 1980s, when Britain
for several years chalked up a surplus. Although a long period of large
deficits would not necessarily be catastrophic, it would probably weaken
international confidence in the UK. It might also require high interest
rates to gain funds from overseas investors via the gilts market.
The main culprit for the slide in the government's finances has been the
recession, which has eaten into tax revenues and pushed up government
spending on unemployment and social security.
If strong recovery were in prospect, the PSBR could be counted on to come
down fairly quickly as tax income rose and the jobless register fell. But to
many economists this appears unlikely.
The main restraints on a sharp upturn include the world economic slowdown,
together with continued nervousness by UK consumers and businesses about
taking on new credit after the large borrowings of the late 1980s. As a
result, real inflation-adjusted growth this year will probably be no more
than about 1 per cent, according to the Treasury and many private-sector
economists.
As for what happens after this year, the Treasury assumed in the Autumn
Statement that growth would pick up relatively quickly, reaching about 3.7
per cent in both 1994-95 and 1995-96 after 1.9 per cent in 1993-94.
Even on this fairly optimistic view, which implies higher growth figures
than those projected by many economists, the Treasury rule of thumb gives
PSBRs for 1994-95 and 1995-96 of Pounds 44.6bn and Pounds 43.7bn
respectively. The arithmetic based on this rule also implies a PSBR in
1993-94 of Pounds 48.3bn.
The rule of thumb, which assumes tax policy stays unchanged, is linked to
how GDP changes in relation to the 'trend' - the optimum rate at which the
economy can expand without either high unemployment or bursts of inflation.
This figure is normally taken to be about 2.25 per cent a year. According to
the rule, a drop in GDP of 1 percentage point below the trend rate for a
specific year leads to a fall of 0.3 points in the ratio of government
revenues to GDP.
Although the rule gives only a rough guide to expected deficits, it can
indicate how periods of high or low growth will affect the PSBR. On the
basis that the economy follows a 'medium growth' path - with GDP expanding
by 1 per cent, 2 per cent and 2 per cent in the three financial years from
1993-94 - the deficit would climb to Pounds 64.4bn in 1995-96, equivalent to
9.3 per cent of GDP. Such large figures appear plausible to many City
economists. Mr Michael Saunders of Salomon Brothers expects the PSBR to
climb to more than Pounds 60bn by 1995-96.
One view is that after the long recession output might rebound quickly, with
projected growth figures even higher than those published by the Treasury in
the Autumn Statement. But this argument is looking less respectable given
that a period of sharp growth, perhaps helped by large cuts in interest
rates, would almost certainly lead to a big rise in imports. As well as
pushing up the large current-account deficit this would certainly lead to
unacceptably high inflation, especially given the pound's depreciation since
its exit from the European exchange rate mechanism.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
