<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / Howe warns of increased taxation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD HOWE, the former Conservative chancellor, yesterday predicted that the
government would have to raise taxes if it was to control public sector
borrowing, Emma Tucker writes.
The election promise to keep taxes low in an economy that encourages free
enterprise would have to stand as a 'medium and long-term pledge', he said.
'It is most important that the government should keep its borrowing
requirement under control and the prospect of borrowing more than Pounds 1bn
a week in the year ahead must be something the chancellor is concerned
with,' he added.
Lord Howe said on BBC radio that a recovery began shortly after he put up
taxes in his 1981 Budget, a fact which should be taken seriously by Mr
Norman Lamont, the chancellor. 'Sooner rather than later is the right time
to change taxes,' he said. 'Increases are tough, but sometimes necessary.'
</TEXT>
