<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / Baghdad stalls on UN missile ultimatum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN, ROBERT MAUTHNER and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, LONDON, SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IRAQ last night delivered an apparently inconclusive reply to the United
Nations' ultimatum that it withdraw missile batteries near the no-fly zone
in the south of the country by this evening.
Mr Nizar Hamdoon, its ambassador to the UN, told western UN representatives
in New York that Iraq had the sovereign right to deploy its military on its
own territory - a response similar to that given earlier by Mr Tariq Aziz,
the deputy prime minister.
There was no clear reaction from the western delegation pending consultation
with their governments. Mr Thomas Richardson, the deputy UK representative,
said 'the essential question' was whether Iraq removed its missiles from
south of the 32nd parallel and not violate the no-fly zone.
He added: 'So in a sense the question depends on what happens on the
ground.'
Mr Hamdoon repeatedly ducked questions about the Soviet-made missiles at
issue. He said: 'I have not addressed the question of the missiles per se.'
Earlier, the US defence department said it had indications that some were
being moved but, with low clouds hampering aerial and satellite surveillance
in the region, there was no word later of their whereabouts and some concern
that they were merely being relocated in more heavily fortified
emplacements.
Officials insisted it was 'premature' to suggest that President Saddam
Hussein was making a 'positive' response to the 48-hour UN ultimatum handed
to Ambassador Hamdoon on Wednesday evening by the US, France, Britain and
Russia, threatening military retaliation. They noted that Iraq had
frequently used the tactic known as 'cheat and retreat' in testing the
resolve of the US and its allies.
In what looked like a propaganda ploy, Mr Hamdoon invited a US congressional
delegation to visit Iraq 'to see the situation in the no-fly zone and
regarding all other disputed issues between the US and Iraq'. This was
presumably a reference to western concerns that President Saddam is
preparing for a crackdown on the Kurds in northern Iraq. British officials
said that unless it was clear the missiles had been moved out of the air
exclusion zone allied aircraft would attack military targets in Iraq within
hours of the ultimatum expiring.
The Soviet-made SA-2 and SA-3 missile batteries were moved adjacent to the
32nd parallel after the downing on December 27 of an Iraqi MiG aircraft by
US jets when it violated the UN-proscribed no-fly zone. President George
Bush was said to be resolute after a meeting with Republican congressmen.
President-elect Bill Clinton's spokesman said he agreed with the policies
being pursued by Mr Bush. 'There will be no toleration of any violations of
the UN resolutions by Saddam,' Mr George Stephanopoulos said. Mr Aziz denied
Iraq was using the impending change of government in Washington as an
opportunity to improve its military posture.
Britain warned Iraq of 'very serious' consequences if it did not remove the
missiles from the no-fly zone.
Mr Zuhair Ibrahim, head of the Iraqi interests section at the Jordanian
Embassy in London, was summoned to the Foreign Office for a 10 minute
meeting. British-Iraqi diplomatic relations were broken off at the start of
the Gulf war in 1991.
An Australian aid worker was shot and killed and another injured after a
village meeting in the UN-controlled Kurdish zone in northern Iraq, the aid
agency CARE Australia said early today, Reuter reports from Sydney. It was
reported that the UN aid programme in the region was subsequently suspended.
Editorial Comment, Page 13
Dangers behind the stand-off with Iraq, Page 3
</TEXT>
