<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 93 / MPs seek probe into all aspects of safety in tankers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON and DAVID OWEN AND DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SUMBURGH, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A POLITICAL row has broken out over the terms of the government's inquiry
into the Braer tanker disaster off Shetland.
As gales prevented salvage teams from boarding the vessel to see how much of
the tanker's cargo of 84,000 tonnes of crude oil remained in its tanks, MPs
and maritime unions called for the inquiry to be broadened to cover all
aspects of tanker safety.
Mr Brian Orrell, assistant general secretary of Numast, the shipping
officers union, said the government was 'skirting round the real issue'. The
union would like to see the inquiry broadened to cover the 'horrendous
decline in safety at sea'.
Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary, said his department's Marine
Accident Investigation Branch would investigate six areas: the causes of the
accident; the action taken to prevent it; the action taken after the event;
the seaworthiness of the vessel; the competence of the crew; and the safety
of navigation.
Mr Chris Smith, Labour's environmental protection spokesman, described the
inquiry - which is to start immediately - as 'totally inadequate.'
The Braer's operator, B&amp;H group, said last night a salvage barge was being
prepared to remove the remaining oil from the tanker. It is expected to
arrive off Shetland on Sunday.
The Braer, which ran aground at Garths Ness in Quendale Bay at the southern
end of Shetland on Tuesday, has not broken up. But bad weather, expected to
continue for at least two days, forced a reduction in flights to spray
chemical dispersants on the oil leaking from the tanker.
Deep oil slicks run for about 5 to 6 miles both north and south from the
tanker. The slicks are about 50 metres wide and are being pushed against the
shore by strong westerly winds.
A thin film of oil, described as a rainbow sheen, runs for 14 miles on the
west side of the island and reaches the entrance of Clift Sound and the
south end of Burra island, bringing it within a few miles of salmon farms,
one of the sectors of the Shetland economy most threatened by the spill.
Shetland Islands Council revealed that it had drawn up a contingency plan to
evacuate residents from the area close to the wreck if atmospheric pollution
were to pose a threat to health, but it said that so far there was no danger
to health. It refused to give details of the plan, which could involve
moving several hundred people.
By yesterday, some 235 dead birds had been found in the area since the
tanker ran aground and 45 live birds had been rescued.
Privately, the emergency co-ordination team acknowledged that the pollution
could have been much worse. The slick is relatively small, most of the oil
is light and 30 per cent of it is thought to be evaporating.
Mr George Sutherland, director of marine operations for Shetland Island
Council, said: 'If anything is good about this incident it is the wind
direction.'
Lord Caithness, the shipping minister, who has been in Shetland since
Wednesday, said he was worried that exaggerated reports about the disaster
would damage the prospects of the Shetland salmon farming and fishing
industries, even though they had not been affected.
US debate on regulations, Page 7
</TEXT>
