<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 93 / County Hall hotel proposal approved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAMBETH Council has approved a planning application by Shirayama Corporation
of Japan to turn County Hall, the former headquarters of the Greater London
Council, into a hotel.
The council's planning committee gave permission to a planning application
at a meeting on Tuesday evening, subject to further consideration later this
month of the community benefits the developer will provide.
The developers plan to convert the building into a 600-bed hotel with
conference and leisure facilities.
Shirayama says it will keep all the historic rooms intact and 'brought back
to their original splendor'. There will be a chapel and a health club in the
basement and a 24-hour public restaurant on the riverside terrace.
The council was advised to accept the planning application for a number of
reasons, including the need for high-quality hotel accommodation in London
and employment potential.
The council originally wanted to keep the building in local government or
public use, favouring a proposal by the London School of Economics to
acquire it. The acrimonious battle between Shirayama and the LSE over the
future of County Hall ended last September when the government rejected the
LSE's bid.
Shirayama is contracted to complete its pounds 65m purchase of the County
Hall riverside building at the end of October. The London Residuary Body
which has the task of disposing of the GLC's assets, launched an
international marketing campaign for the remainder of the 5-hectare site
last November.
</TEXT>
