<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 93 / (CORRECTED) Bricklayer wins Pounds 1,500 harassment award
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 8th January 1993) appended to this article.
A BRICKLAYER has won against a London council one of the highest recorded
settlements in compensation for sexual and racial harassment at work,
Catherine Milton writes.
Ms Tracie Simpson, 28, told an industrial tribunal that local officials from
one union had participated in her harassment while Ucatt, the building
union, had been slow to give effective support.
Greenwich Council agreed to pay Ms Simpson Pounds 1,500. She lost her job in
October 1991 and is now unemployed, with no plans to return to construction.
The settlement came after the tribunal decided her case should be heard even
though she failed to raise her claim within the three-month time limit. The
tribunal accepted that she had experienced 'considerable sexual and racial
harassment', some of which was perpetrated by the 'lower tiers of
management' and that the council had failed to take 'effective action' to
stop it.
CORRECTION
MS TRACIE SIMPSON won Pounds 15,000 compensation for sexual and racial
harassment from Greenwich council in London and not Pounds 1,500 as reported
yesterday.
</TEXT>
